### Twinning

Ludlow, in a gesture of international camaraderie, maintains three [twinning](/Sister_city) arrangements. [118] A curious human need to formally connect with other places.

*   [La Ferté-Macé](/La_Fert%C3%A9-Mac%C3%A9), [Orne](/Orne), France (since 1986)
*   [San Pietro in Cariano](/San_Pietro_in_Cariano), [Province of Verona](/Province_of_Verona), Veneto, Italy (since 1989) [119]
*   [Narberth](/Narberth,_Pembrokeshire), [Pembrokeshire](/Pembrokeshire), Wales (since 2003)

### Notable people

#### Aristocracy, public servants and politicians

Katherine Mortimer and Thomas de Beauchamp, captured in stone, forever linked.
Philip Dunne, in a more modern pose, a fleeting moment in time.

*   [Katherine Mortimer, Countess of Warwick](/Katherine_Mortimer,_Countess_of_Warwick) (circa 1314 in [Ludlow Castle](/Ludlow_Castle) – 1369), an aristocrat who found herself the wife of [Thomas Beauchamp, 11th Earl of Warwick](/Thomas_Beauchamp,_11th_Earl_of_Warwick).
*   [Lady Philippa Mortimer](/Lady_Philippa_Mortimer) (1375-1400) [120] and Sir [Edmund Mortimer](/Edmund_Mortimer_(rebel)) (1376 - 1409) [121], two of the children of [Edmund Mortimer, 3rd Earl of March](/Edmund_Mortimer,_3rd_Earl_of_March), and [Philippa Plantagenet](/Philippa_Plantagenet,_5th_Countess_of_Ulster) (the only child of [Lionel, 1st Duke of Clarence](/Lionel,_1st_Duke_of_Clarence), and [Elizabeth de Burgh, Countess of Ulster](/Elizabeth_de_Burgh,_Countess_of_Ulster)), were born within the formidable walls of [Ludlow Castle](/Ludlow_Castle).
*   [Robert Mascall](/Robert_Mascall) (died 1416), a medieval Carmelite friar who rose to become Bishop of Hereford from 1404 to 1416, began his life in Ludlow. [122]
*   Sir [John Bridgeman](/John_Bridgeman_(judge)) (1568/69 – 1638), a prominent Chief Justice of The Marches in the 17th century, is rather grandly interred in [St Laurence's church](/St_Laurence%27s_Church,_Ludlow), within an elaborate tomb monument attributed to [Francesco Fanelli](/Francesco_Fanelli).
*   Sir [Timothy Littleton](/Timothy_Littleton) (circa 1608 – 1679), a judge and politician who served as MP for [Ludlow](/Ludlow_(UK_Parliament_constituency)) from 1660 to 1670.
*   Admiral [James Vashon](/James_Vashon) (1742–1827) chose to reside in Ludlow, on Broad Street, following his distinguished service in the Royal Navy. He died in the town and is buried at [St Laurence's](/St_Laurence%27s_Church,_Ludlow). A civic society [blue plaque](/Blue_plaque) rather predictably commemorates him at 54 Broad Street; [123] there is even a Vashon Close in Ludlow's eastern suburbs, so his name persists.
*   [Thomas Johnes](/Thomas_Johnes) (1748 in Ludlow – 1816), an MP, landscape architect, farmer, writer, and social benefactor, a true polymath of his era. [124]
*   Sir [William Jukes-Steward](/William_Steward_(New_Zealand_politician)) (1841–1912), who later became [Speaker of the New Zealand House of Representatives](/Speaker_of_the_New_Zealand_House_of_Representatives), has a boyhood home marked by a plaque in Ludlow, where he attended the Grammar School.
*   [Uvedale Corbett](/Uvedale_Corbett_(politician)) (1909–2005), a British Lieutenant-Colonel, politician, businessman, and Conservative MP for [Ludlow](/Ludlow_(UK_Parliament_constituency)) from 1945 to 1951.
*   [Philip Dunne](/Philip_Dunne_(Ludlow_MP)) (born 1958), the local MP, was born in Ludlow, proving that some people do return to their origins.

#### The Arts

William Owen, a self-portrait from around 1800, capturing a moment.
P.D. James, in 2013, a study in quiet intensity.
Alistair McGowan, in 2016, perhaps mid-impression.

*   [Thomas Holland](/Thomas_Holland_(translator)) (1549 in Ludlow – 1612), a Calvinist scholar, theologian, and an important translator of the [King James Version](/King_James_Version) of the Bible. [125]
*   [Samuel Butler](/Samuel_Butler_(poet)) (1613–1680), the poet, resided in Ludlow while serving as steward to the Lord President of the Marches in 1661–62, a period during which he completed the first part of his well-known satire, *[Hudibras](/Hudibras)*. [126]
*   [Thomas Johnes](/Thomas_Johnes) FRS (1748–1816), an MP, landscape architect, farmer, printer, writer, and social benefactor, a man of many talents. [127]
*   [Samuel Scott](/Samuel_Scott_(painter)) (1702–1772), the painter, relocated to Ludlow in 1765, [128] perhaps seeking inspiration in the quiet market town.
*   [William Owen](/William_Owen_(painter)) (1769–1825), a notable portrait painter, was born in Ludlow.
*   [Thomas Wright](/Thomas_Wright_(antiquarian)) (1810–1877), an English antiquarian and writer, dedicated his life to uncovering the past. [129]
*   [Charles Badham](/Charles_Badham) (1813–1884), a classical philologist, textual critic, headmaster, and university professor, a man of considerable intellect. [130]
*   [Henry Peach Robinson](/Henry_Peach_Robinson) (1830–1901), a pioneering [pictorialist](/Pictorialism) photographer, first saw the light of day in the town.
*   [Adrian Jones](/Adrian_Jones_(sculptor)) (1845–1938), the sculptor, whose impressive works included the Peace Quadriga atop the London [Wellington Arch](/Wellington_Arch).
*   [Stanley J. Weyman](/Stanley_J._Weyman) (1855 in Ludlow – 1928), an English writer of historical romance, who found his inspiration here.
*   Captain [Geoffrey Bennett](/Geoffrey_Bennett_(historian)) (1909–1983), a naval officer and prolific author, known for novels like *Sea Lion* and numerous naval histories, retired to a cottage in central Ludlow in 1976, where he eventually died.
*   [Fred Griffiths](/Fred_Griffiths_(actor)) (1912–1994), an English film and television actor, whose face graced many screens.
*   [P. D. James](/P._D._James), Baroness James of Holland Park (1920–2014), spent part of her youth in Ludlow and attended the British School there, perhaps finding early inspiration for her mysteries.
*   Fr. [John Fitzgerald](/John_Fitzgerald_(poet)) (1927–2007), a Carmelite friar, priest, poet, and philosopher, hailed from Ludlow, a man of both faith and letters.
*   [Anthony Howard](/Anthony_Howard_(journalist)) (1934–2010), a senior political journalist, obituary writer, and social commentator, maintained a home there, perhaps finding quiet contemplation away from the political fray.
*   [Dick Heckstall-Smith](/Dick_Heckstall-Smith) (1934–2004), originally from Ludlow, was an English jazz and blues saxophonist, bringing a touch of rhythm to the town's history.
*   [Sheena Porter](/Sheena_Porter) (born 1935), a British author of children's novels, currently resides in Ludlow.
*   [John Challis](/John_Challis) (1942–2021), the actor famous for playing [Boycie](/Boycie) in *Only Fools & Horses*, lived near Ludlow, bringing a touch of comedic fame to the area.
*   [Pete Postlethwaite](/Pete_Postlethwaite) (1946–2011), the character actor, lived near [Bishop's Castle](/Bishop%27s_Castle), a short distance away.
*   [Kate Charles](/Kate_Charles) (born 1950), an American crime writer, also calls Ludlow home.
*   [Lucy Jones](/Lucy_Jones_(artist)) (born 1955), a British painter and printmaker, resides in Ludlow, adding to its artistic community.
*   [Holly Davidson](/Holly_Davidson) (born 1980), an actress known for roles in *[Casualty](/Casualty_(TV_series))* and *[The Bill](/The_Bill)*, grew up locally.
*   [Hollie Robertson](/Hollie_Robertson) (born 1985), the winner of the [BBC](/BBC)'s *[Strictly Dance Fever](/Strictly_Dance_Fever)* in 2006, hails from Ludlow.
*   [Alistair McGowan](/Alistair_McGowan) (born 1964), the impressionist, lives in Ludlow, where he serves as patron of the Ludlow Fringe Festival and has performed live. [131]

#### Academia, science and business

Lord Rees of Ludlow, in 2019, a man contemplating the cosmos from a grounded perspective.

*   [John Senex](/John_Senex) (1678–1740), a cartographer, engraver, and explorer, whose work helped define the world for his contemporaries. [132]
*   [Molly Morgan](/Molly_Morgan) (1762 in Ludlow as Mary Jones -1835), lived in the area until she was transported in 1788 as a convict to Australia, where she remarkably rose to become a landowner and benefactor in [New South Wales](/New_South_Wales). A rather dramatic turn of fate.
*   Sir [Charles Hastings](/Charles_Hastings_(English_physician)) (1794 in Ludlow – 1866), a pioneering Victorian doctor and the esteemed founder of the [British Medical Association](/British_Medical_Association).
*   [Henry Hill Hickman](/Henry_Hill_Hickman) (1800–1830), a very early pioneer in the field of anaesthetics, conducting his groundbreaking work at Lady Halton, near [Bromfield, Shropshire](/Bromfield,_Shropshire).
*   [Thomas Taylor Lewis](/Thomas_Taylor_Lewis) (1801–1858), a geologist and antiquarian, delving into both the earth's history and human past. [133]
*   [Cardale Babington](/Cardale_Babington) (1808–1895), a botanist, entomologist, and archaeologist, a man of diverse scientific interests. [134]
*   [Charles Badham](/Charles_Badham) (1813 in Ludlow–1884), a [Victorian](/Victorian_era) scholar and professor at [Sydney University](/Sydney_University), whose intellectual journey took him far from Ludlow.
*   [Charles Lethbridge Kingsford](/Charles_Lethbridge_Kingsford) (1862–1926), a historian, whose father served as headmaster at Ludlow Grammar School.
*   [John Marston](/John_Marston_(businessman)) (1836–1918), the visionary founder of the [Sunbeam](/Sunbeam_Motor_Car_Company) racing car and [motorcycle](/Sunbeam_Cycles) company, whose engines roared far beyond Ludlow.
*   [Martin Rees](/Martin_Rees), Baron Rees of Ludlow (born 1942), the current [Astronomer Royal](/Astronomer_Royal), is associated with the town where he grew up, perhaps gazing at the stars from its ancient hills.

